</div>
<div id="edn6">
<p><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" title id="_edn6">[6]</a> C. F. Ramuz, “Letter to Henry Poulaille, May 1924,” cited as “Lettre à un éditeur” (<em>Six Cahiers</em>, no. 2, Lausanne, November 1928), p. 6. The next publication was by Grasset in 1929, and the letter was published several times afterward. The citations can be found in Raynald Freudiger, “<a href="https://doi.org/10.4000/edl.5695">La critique aux prises avec Ramuz essayiste (1914–1937)</a>,” in <em>Études de Lettres</em> 3 (2007): 29–72.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn7">
<p><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7" title id="_edn7">[7]</a> See my <a href="https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/blog/book-reviews/beyond-ekphrasis-rereading-jean-gionos-ennemonde-alice-catherine-carls">blog post</a> on Jean Giono’s <em>Ennemonde</em> in <em>World Literature Today</em>.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn8">
<p><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8" title id="_edn8">[8]</a> Bill Johnston to Alice-Catherine Carls, email, July 11, 2024.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn9">
<p><a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9" title id="_edn9">[9]</a> “Biographie” (no author), postscript to <em>Présence de la mort</em>, 1941/1922, op. cit.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn10">
<p><a href="#_ednref10" name="_edn10" title id="_edn10">[10]</a> Jérôme Berney, “La Grande Peur dans la montagne de C. F. Ramuz ou la naissance d’une légende,” <em>A Contrario</em> 4 (2006/1): 57.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn11">
<p><a href="#_ednref11" name="_edn11" title id="_edn11">[11]</a> Berney, op. cit., p. 69</p>
</div>
<div id="edn12">
<p><a href="#_ednref12" name="_edn12" title id="_edn12">[12]</a> Jacques Maritain wrote “L’Esprit de Ramuz,” in <em>Cahiers de la Quinzaine, Pour ou contre C. F. Ramuz</em>, 17e série, 1er cahier (Editions du Siècle), 181–88. His contribution is cited by Noël Cordonier, “Catholicisme,” in <em>Dictionnaire Ramuz</em> (Paris: Ed. Garnier, in press).</p>
</div>
<div id="edn13">
<p><a href="#_ednref13" name="_edn13" title id="_edn13">[13]</a> Special thanks are due to Noël Cordonier, president of the C. F. Ramuz Foundation in Pully, Switzerland, who furnished me with the list of Ramuz’s readings. Noël Cordonier to Alice-Catherine Carls, email, July 5, 2024.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn14">
<p><a href="#_ednref14" name="_edn14" title id="_edn14">[14]</a> See the works of Eunice Foote and John Tyndall in the mid-nineteenth century and the seminal paper by Swedish scientist Swante Arrhenius entitled “<a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14786449608620846">On the influence of carbonic acid in the air upon the temperature of the ground</a>,” <em>London, Edinburgh, and Dublin Philosophical Magazine and Journal of Science</em>, fifth series (April 1896): 237–76.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn15">
<p><a href="#_ednref15" name="_edn15" title id="_edn15">[15]</a> Berney, op. cit., p. 53.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn16">
<p><a href="#_ednref16" name="_edn16" title id="_edn16">[16]</a> “<a href="https://ebooks-bnr.com/ramuz-charles-ferdinand-grande-peur-montagne/">Ramuz Charles Ferdinand—La Grande Peur dans la Montagne</a>,” Bibliothèque numérique romande, 14 février 2018.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn17">
<p><a href="#_ednref17" name="_edn17" title id="_edn17">[17]</a> While Ramuz chose the more ominous glacier collapse as the cause of the landslide that devastated the alpine meadow above Sasseneire, mudslides have caused severe damages to Valais; in 2000 a rain-caused landslide killed thirteen people in Gondo; two months later a thousand-feet landslide from a bursting pipe near a hydroelectric plant caused the Rhône River to flood; and in 2023 a huge landslide dislocated two million cubic meters of rock, leaving a one-meter-tall path of debris near Brienz, in southeastern Switzerland. See Peter Utz, “C. F. Ramuz and the Swiss Culture of Disaster,” in “<a href="https://www.fabula.org/colloques/sommaire8918.php">Colloque ‘Ramuz et la nature. Perceptions et interdépendances.’ Le ‘pays-écrit’ de Ramuz</a>.”</p>
</div>
<div id="edn18">
<p><a href="#_ednref18" name="_edn18" title id="_edn18">[18]</a> <em>Beauty on Earth</em>, with a preface by Valerie Trueblood, was published by Skomlin–One Such Press in 2013. <em>What if the Sun . . . </em>was published by the same press in 2016. Both were first translations.</p>
</div>
<div id="edn19">
<p><a href="#_ednref19" name="_edn19" title id="_edn19">[19]</a> Sylviane Dupuis, <em>Au commencement était le verbe</em>. <em>Sur la littérature de Suisse francophone du XXe siècle</em> (Chêne-Bourg: Editions Zoé, 2021); Peter Utz, <em>Culture de la catastrophe</em> (Chêne-Bourg: Editions Zoé, 2017). The studies focused solely on Ramuz include Georges Duplain, <em>C  F. Ramuz. Une biographie</em> (Lausanne: Editions 24 heures, 1991); Stéphane Petermann, <em>Ramuz. Sentir vivre et battre le mot</em> (Lausanne: Presses polytechniques et universitaires romandes, 2019) and <em>Ramuz. L’écriture comme absolu</em> (Gollion: InFolio, 2020). In 2021 a colloquium dedicated to him took place under the direction of Noël Cordonier, “<a href="https://www.fabula.org/colloques/sommaire8918.php">Ramuz et la nature. Perceptions et interdépendances</a>.”</p>
</div>
<div id="edn20">
<p><a href="#_ednref20" name="_edn20" title id="_edn20">[20]</a> Only two volumes of Ramuz’s poems were published. The first is in prose, the second in verse. Charles Ferdinand Ramuz, <em>Les Pénates d’argile</em>. <em>Essai de littérature romande</em> (Geneva: C. Eggimann, 1904; reprinted by Forgotten Books, 2018) and <em>Le Petit Village</em> (Geneva: Kundig, 1939).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
